  "business_context": "Soft Credit records solve a recognition problem unique to nonprofit fundraising: a single donation often involves multiple stakeholders beyond the legal donor. A husband's $10,000 gift should also recognize his wife (household soft credit) so she's invited to donor events. A donation that came in from a Donor Advised Fund (DAF — like Fidelity Charitable) is legally from the DAF, but the individual recommending the gift should receive cultivation credit. A board member who introduced the org to a corporate funder deserves recognition even though the corporation made the actual gift. Soft credits let organizations track these contributions without double-counting revenue. NPSP has the most elaborate model: separate Partial Soft Credit and Account Soft Credit objects, plus Opportunity Contact Role records that auto-generate soft credits, with nightly batch rollup to Contact and Household Account level. CiviCRM has Soft Credit as a child of Contribution with type discriminators (Solicited, In Honor Of, In Memory Of, Workplace Giving). Bloomerang uses Acknowledgement records with credit-share percentages. The B2B systems have no native concept and would require custom build-out. When interviewing clients, surface \"Soft Credit\" by asking whether they need to recognize spouses for joint giving, DAF advisors for grants from their funds, or influencers/connectors for gifts they helped secure.",
  "catalog_id": "soft-credit",
